MOFA+ CLL Analysis - Simplified Pipeline

Based on MOFA2 Tutorial by Ricard Argelaguet and Britta Velten

2025-12-13

Introduction

This vignette demonstrates MOFA+ (Multi-Omics Factor Analysis) on a CLL (Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia) multi-omics dataset. The data consists of four omics:

  • DNA methylation (4248 features)
  • RNA-seq / mRNA (5000 features)
  • Somatic mutations (69 features)
  • Drug response (310 features)

from N=200 patients with CLL.

Key approach: We load a pre-trained model to avoid Python/R compatibility issues, then focus on analysis and interpretation.

2. Load Pre-trained MOFA Model

The original tutorial provides a pre-trained model. This approach: - Avoids Python/mofapy2 compatibility issues - Guarantees reproducibility - Allows immediate analysis

cat("=== Loading Pre-trained MOFA Model ===\n")
## === Loading Pre-trained MOFA Model ===
cat("Downloading from EBI FTP...\n\n")
## Downloading from EBI FTP...
# Load the pre-trained model from the official repository
MOFAobject <- readRDS(url("http://ftp.ebi.ac.uk/pub/databases/mofa/cll_vignette/MOFA2_CLL.rds"))

cat(" Model loaded successfully!\n\n")
##  Model loaded successfully!
# Display model summary
print(MOFAobject)
## Trained MOFA with the following characteristics: 
##  Number of views: 4 
##  Views names: Drugs Methylation mRNA Mutations 
##  Number of features (per view): 310 4248 5000 69 
##  Number of groups: 1 
##  Groups names: group1 
##  Number of samples (per group): 200 
##  Number of factors: 15

Add Sample Metadata to Model

# Add clinical metadata to the MOFA object
samples_metadata(MOFAobject) <- CLL_metadata

cat(" Metadata added to model\n")
##  Metadata added to model
cat("Available covariates:", paste(colnames(samples_metadata(MOFAobject)), collapse=", "), "\n")
## Available covariates: sample, Gender, age, TTT, TTD, treatedAfter, died, IGHV, trisomy12, group

4. Variance Decomposition

The most important insight from MOFA is understanding which factors explain variance in which data modalities.

Variance Explained per Factor

plot_variance_explained(MOFAobject, max_r2 = 15)

Key insights: - Factor 1 captures variation across ALL modalities important disease driver - Factor 2 is specific to drug response - Factor 3 captures variation in multiple modalities except methylation

Total Variance Explained

plot_variance_explained(MOFAobject, plot_total = TRUE)[[2]]

5. Factor Correlation

Good models should have largely uncorrelated factors.

plot_factor_cor(MOFAobject)

6. Characterization of Factor 1 (IGHV Mutation)

Association with Clinical Covariates

correlate_factors_with_covariates(MOFAobject, 
  covariates = c("Gender", "died", "age"), 
  plot = "log_pval"
)

Plot Factor 1 Values

plot_factor(MOFAobject, 
  factors = 1, 
  color_by = "Factor1"
)

Feature Weights for Mutations View

plot_weights(MOFAobject,
  view = "Mutations",
  factor = 1,
  nfeatures = 10,
  abs = FALSE
)

Key finding: IGHV mutation status has the largest weight for Factor 1!

Visualize IGHV Status

plot_factor(MOFAobject, 
  factors = 1, 
  color_by = "IGHV",
  dodge = TRUE,
  add_violin = TRUE
)

mRNA Expression Weights

  view = "mRNA",

  view = "Drugs",

  features = 4,
  sign = "positive",
  color_by = "trisomy12"
) + labs(y = "Drug response (cell viability)")

8. Combined Analysis: Factor 1 vs Factor 3

This plot classifies patients into clinical subgroups based on their multi-omic profiles.

p <- plot_factors(MOFAobject, 
  factors = c(1, 3), 
  color_by = "IGHV",
  shape_by = "trisomy12",
  dot_size = 2.5,
  show_missing = TRUE
)

p <- p + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = -1, linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = -0.5, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(title = "Patient Stratification by MOFA Factors",
       subtitle = "Based on IGHV mutation and Trisomy 12 status")

print(p)

Clinical Significance: This plot stratifies 200 CLL patients into 4 molecular subgroups that predict drug response and survival!

Run GSEA

# Run enrichment analysis on Factor 1
enrichment_results <- run_enrichment(MOFAobject, 
  feature.sets = reactomeGS, 
  view = "mRNA",
  factors = 1:5,
  set.statistic = "mean.diff",
  statistical.test = "parametric"
)

Plot Enrichment Results

# Plot enrichment results (with error handling for no significant pathways)
tryCatch({
  plot_enrichment(enrichment_results, 
    factor = 1, 
    max.pathways = 15,
    alpha = 0.1  # Relaxed threshold for demonstration
  )
}, error = function(e) {
  cat("Note: No significant pathways at default threshold.\n")
  cat("Showing top pathways regardless of significance:\n")
  # Display top results manually
  results_df <- enrichment_results$pval.adj[, 1, drop = FALSE]
  results_df <- data.frame(pathway = rownames(results_df), pval_adj = results_df[,1])
  results_df <- results_df[order(results_df$pval_adj), ]
  print(head(results_df, 15))
})

Summary

This analysis demonstrated how MOFA+ integrates multiple omics to identify:

  1. Factor 1 (IGHV): The major source of variation, linked to IGHV mutation status
  2. Factor 3 (Trisomy 12): Second major factor, linked to trisomy 12 status
  3. Patient stratification: Four clinical subgroups based on molecular profiles
  4. Pathway enrichment: Biological processes underlying each factor

These factors can be used for: - Predicting treatment response - Patient stratification - Biomarker discovery - Survival analysis
